1 uduotis:

For this exercise, use the monthly Australian short-term overseas visitors data, May 1985April 2005. (Data set: visitors in expsmooth package.)

library("expsmooth")
  1. Use ets to find the best model for these data and record the training set RMSE. You should find that the best model is ETS(M,A,M).
frc1 <- ets(visitors); frc1[13]
## $method
## [1] "ETS(M,Ad,M)"
rmse1<-accuracy(frc1)[2]; rmse1
## [1] 15.07221
  • Matome, jog geriausia modeli ir pasirinko ETS(M,A,M) bei RMSE = 15.07221.
  1. We will now check how much larger the one-step RMSE is on out-of-sample data using time series cross-validation. The following code will compute the result, beginning with four years of data in the training set. Check that you understand what the code is doing. Ask if you dont.
k <- 48 # minimum size for training set
n <- length(visitors) # Total number of observations
e <- visitors*NA # Vector to record one-step forecast errors
for(i in 48:(n-1))
  {
  train <- ts(visitors[1:i],freq=12)
  fit <- ets(train, "MAM", damped=FALSE)
  fc <- forecast(fit,h=1)$mean
  e[i] <- visitors[i+1]-fc
  }
rmse2 <- sqrt(mean(e^2,na.rm=TRUE)); rmse2
## [1] 18.31503
  • Skaiiuoja paklaidas tarp prognozs reikmi bei turim duomen reikmi. Ieko RMSE.
  • I io ciklo, gauname RMSE = 18.31503. Jis yra didesnis nei prie tai gautas. ia paklaidos yra skaiiuojamos tarp prognozs ir inom reikmi.
  1. What would happen in the above loop if I had set train <- visitors[1:i]?
k1 <- 48 # minimum size for training set
n1 <- length(visitors) # Total number of observations
e1 <- visitors*NA # Vector to record one-step forecast errors
for(i in 48:(n1-1))
  {
  train1 <- visitors[1:i]
  fit1 <- ets(train1, "MAM", damped=FALSE)
  fc1 <- forecast(fit1,h=1)$mean
  e1[i] <- visitors[i+1]-fc1
  }
## Error in ets(train1, "MAM", damped = FALSE): Nonseasonal data
sqrt(mean(e1^2,na.rm=TRUE))
## [1] NaN
  • Atlikus pakeitimus meta klaid, nebeapskaiiuoja RMSE. Taip yra, nes duomenys nebepriklauso laiko eilui klasei.

  • Matome, jog paklaid svyravimai vis didja. Taip gali bti, nes ir duomen sklaida auga.
  1. How does this problem bias the comparison of the RMSE values from (1a) and (1b)? (Hint: think about the effect of the missing values in e.)
  • 1a RMSE maesnis u 1b. Tai lemia ne vienodas duomen skaiius prognozei - 1a daugiau duomen. RMSE atsivelgia turimus duomenis bei prognoze, todl kai daugiau duomen gaunasi paklaidos maesns.
  1. In practice, we will not know that the best model on the whole data set is ETS(M,A,M) until we observe all the data. So a more realistic analysis would be to allow ets to select a different model each time through the loop. Calculate the RMSE using this approach. (Warning: it will take a while as there are a lot of models to fit.)
for(i in 48:(n-1))
  {
  train <- ts(visitors[1:i],freq=12)
  fit <- ets(train)
  fc <- forecast(fit,h=1)$mean
  e[i] <- visitors[i+1]-fc
  }
rmse3 <- sqrt(mean(e^2,na.rm=TRUE)); rmse3
## [1] 18.62526
  • Gauname RMSE=18.62526
  1. How does the RMSE computed in (1f) compare to that computed in (1b)? Does the re-selection of a model at each step make much difference?
  • b dalies RMSE=18.31503, o f dalies RMSE=18.62526. Taigi reikmingo skirtumo tarp i reikmi nra ir nra didelio skirtumo kur metod rinktis. Taiau patartina bt pirmj, nes nra prasms kiekvien kart leisti ibandyti visus galimus ETS modelius, nes tai ugaita laiko.
